- Our final special
presentation actually came from,

00:00:13.989 --> 00:00:16.411
I think our Planning
and Advisory Committee

00:00:16.411 --> 00:00:19.739
as well as the evaluations from last year,

00:00:19.739 --> 00:00:24.727
and so this is a very
special, unique presentation

00:00:24.727 --> 00:00:28.161
from Rick Guidotti, who is right here,

00:00:28.161 --> 00:00:30.165
a fashion photographer,

00:00:30.165 --> 00:00:32.376
who has done something pretty incredible

00:00:32.376 --> 00:00:35.901
called the Frame Project
and so we're gonna let Rick

00:00:35.901 --> 00:00:37.479
do his thing.

00:00:37.479 --> 00:00:38.402
Alright.

00:00:38.402 --> 00:00:39.333
- Thank you.

00:00:39.333 --> 00:00:40.257
- Thank you.

00:00:40.257 --> 00:00:41.361
- Thank you so much.

00:00:41.361 --> 00:00:43.327
Hey, I'm so thrilled to be here.

00:00:43.327 --> 00:00:44.160
Thanks for having me.

00:00:44.160 --> 00:00:47.492
So, here's the thing for
changing it, that would be great.

00:00:47.492 --> 00:00:49.235
So, I'll tell you a little about,

00:00:49.235 --> 00:00:51.053
I'll give you a little
history on Positive Exposure.

00:00:51.053 --> 00:00:54.048
I am a fashion photographer
based in New York City

00:00:54.048 --> 00:00:57.146
but I also lived in Milan
and Paris for several years

00:00:57.146 --> 00:01:00.425
and got to work with some pretty
amazing models and clients

00:01:00.425 --> 00:01:03.857
and this, of course, is
Claudia for an Elle shoot.

00:01:03.857 --> 00:01:06.292
This is Marie Claire.

00:01:06.292 --> 00:01:08.751
I did a lot of work for the
House of Ives Saint Laurent

00:01:08.751 --> 00:01:09.703
in Paris.

00:01:09.703 --> 00:01:11.035
So I lived in Paris for quite a bit.

00:01:11.035 --> 00:01:12.357
I did a lot of portraiture as well.

00:01:12.357 --> 00:01:14.257
That's a portrait of Mr. Saint Laurent

00:01:14.257 --> 00:01:18.252
and that's one of the images
from our global campaign.

00:01:18.252 --> 00:01:20.319
French Elle magazine.

00:01:20.319 --> 00:01:23.229
This is New York Style magazine.

00:01:23.229 --> 00:01:24.312
Marie Claire.

00:01:25.592 --> 00:01:27.220
English Marie Claire.

00:01:27.220 --> 00:01:30.856
French Elle and, of course,
here's our beautiful, Cindy,

00:01:30.856 --> 00:01:32.704
from a Revlon shoot.

00:01:32.704 --> 00:01:34.258
So I got to work with lots of great models

00:01:34.258 --> 00:01:36.395
and lots of great clients and
I traveled around the world.

00:01:36.395 --> 00:01:38.011
I was living in Milan and it was amazing

00:01:38.011 --> 00:01:40.397
but it was also really quite frustrating

00:01:40.397 --> 00:01:44.931
'cause I was always, always,
always told who was beautiful.

00:01:44.931 --> 00:01:47.720
You know, and I was told who
the model of the moment was

00:01:47.720 --> 00:01:49.061
and we all had to photograph that face

00:01:49.061 --> 00:01:51.021
and then it would change the next season

00:01:51.021 --> 00:01:53.031
and we'd photograph that
face the next season

00:01:53.031 --> 00:01:56.263
but I was always told who's
beautiful and as an artist,

00:01:56.263 --> 00:01:58.147
I never, ever, ever saw

00:01:58.147 --> 00:01:59.675
and I continue never to see beauty

00:01:59.675 --> 00:02:02.637
only on covers of magazines.

00:02:02.637 --> 00:02:05.449
It exists there but it
doesn't only exist there.

00:02:05.449 --> 00:02:06.792
I see beauty everywhere.

00:02:06.792 --> 00:02:09.646
I was leaving my studio one
afternoon in New York City,

00:02:09.646 --> 00:02:11.548
running down Park Avenue after doing

00:02:11.548 --> 00:02:13.463
a huge casting for Elle magazine.

00:02:13.463 --> 00:02:16.255
I pretty much saw every model
in town, it was amazing,

00:02:16.255 --> 00:02:18.862
but I was just running
down Park Avenue and there,

00:02:18.862 --> 00:02:20.970
waiting for the bus at Park and 20th,

00:02:20.970 --> 00:02:23.314
was this stunning girl.

00:02:23.314 --> 00:02:26.776
She had long white, white,
white hair, she had pale skin,

00:02:26.776 --> 00:02:29.871
she had this genetic
condition called albinism.

00:02:29.871 --> 00:02:32.414
I knew the terms was albino.

00:02:32.414 --> 00:02:34.494
That's what I knew and she was stunning

00:02:34.494 --> 00:02:37.614
but I never model that
looked like this girl.

00:02:37.614 --> 00:02:40.186
She had never been included
in that beauty standard

00:02:40.186 --> 00:02:41.764
and I wanted to grab her

00:02:41.764 --> 00:02:43.213
and say I have to take your photograph,

00:02:43.213 --> 00:02:44.230
you're amazing,

00:02:44.230 --> 00:02:46.235
but the bus came and she
got on the bus and took off.

00:02:46.235 --> 00:02:47.360
(audience laughs)

00:02:47.360 --> 00:02:48.632
And you know, I always say this,

00:02:48.632 --> 00:02:50.545
and I always say this in my presentation -

00:02:50.545 --> 00:02:52.340
I'm actually quite
pleased that the bus came

00:02:52.340 --> 00:02:55.612
because she was 12 years old
and I would be in prison.

00:02:55.612 --> 00:02:56.630
(audience laughs)

00:02:56.630 --> 00:02:57.796
So I'm glad that that didn't happen.

00:02:57.796 --> 00:02:59.872
So she was stunning but I just ran down

00:02:59.872 --> 00:03:02.688
to the local Barnes &amp; Noble
to find more photographs

00:03:02.688 --> 00:03:04.522
of this gorgeous girl or friends of hers

00:03:04.522 --> 00:03:06.317
with the genetic condition albinism.

00:03:06.317 --> 00:03:09.424
I went to the School of
Visual Arts in New York City

00:03:09.424 --> 00:03:10.637
so I only went to an art school.

00:03:10.637 --> 00:03:12.990
I never saw a medical textbook photograph

00:03:12.990 --> 00:03:14.972
or a medical textbook prior to that moment

00:03:14.972 --> 00:03:17.070
and there was my first medical textbook,

00:03:17.070 --> 00:03:19.430
I pulled it off the shelf
so excited to open it up

00:03:19.430 --> 00:03:21.807
to albinism to find images
of this gorgeous girl

00:03:21.807 --> 00:03:24.439
or her friends but instead
of finding those images,

00:03:24.439 --> 00:03:26.629
I found these images.

00:03:26.629 --> 00:03:29.496
I found images of the
bright red albino eye.

00:03:29.496 --> 00:03:31.677
This kid did not have bright red eyes.

00:03:31.677 --> 00:03:33.292
She had beautiful blue eyes

00:03:33.292 --> 00:03:35.518
and I saw thousands of
photographs of people

00:03:35.518 --> 00:03:38.478
in cancer clinics with great
big open festering wounds

00:03:38.478 --> 00:03:39.644
and cancers.

00:03:39.644 --> 00:03:41.496
I'm thinking this is horrible!

00:03:41.496 --> 00:03:44.703
But then even more disturbing
where the countless images

00:03:44.703 --> 00:03:47.401
that I saw of kids up against
walls in doctors' offices,

00:03:47.401 --> 00:03:50.326
usually naked with those
black bars across their eyes

00:03:50.326 --> 00:03:51.838
standing up against the wall.

00:03:51.838 --> 00:03:55.056
See and I'm thinking this
is not what I'm looking for.

00:03:55.056 --> 00:03:57.152
Where are those photographs
of that gorgeous kid?

00:03:57.152 --> 00:03:59.044
So I very quickly closed those books.

00:03:59.044 --> 00:04:00.675
I figured, an encyclopedia!

00:04:00.675 --> 00:04:02.833
That's where I'm gonna
find 'em but instead,

00:04:02.833 --> 00:04:04.036
and I grabbed an encyclopedia,

00:04:04.036 --> 00:04:06.317
but instead of finding
photographs of this gorgeous kid,

00:04:06.317 --> 00:04:09.084
I found the freak albino
family in the circus

00:04:09.084 --> 00:04:11.322
and then I started doing more research

00:04:11.322 --> 00:04:14.671
and I found all these
incredible negative portrayals

00:04:14.671 --> 00:04:16.767
in Hollywood feature films from Powder,

00:04:16.767 --> 00:04:19.410
who had albinism 'cause his
mother was struck by lightning

00:04:19.410 --> 00:04:20.722
when she was pregnant with him,

00:04:20.722 --> 00:04:24.417
to the Princess Bride, the pit of despair,

00:04:24.417 --> 00:04:26.194
to the Matrix Reloaded,

00:04:26.194 --> 00:04:28.384
these evil ghostlike
characters that would come

00:04:28.384 --> 00:04:30.529
and they'd wreak havoc
and then they'd disappear

00:04:30.529 --> 00:04:32.272
to even most recently,

00:04:32.272 --> 00:04:34.499
the Da Vinci Code, where the Da Vinci,

00:04:34.499 --> 00:04:36.567
it was the evil Silas driving around Paris

00:04:36.567 --> 00:04:37.929
at night shooting at people.

00:04:37.929 --> 00:04:40.219
One of the first things I
discovered in my research

00:04:40.219 --> 00:04:42.723
about albinism that
people with this condition

00:04:42.723 --> 00:04:44.205
have a visual impairment.

00:04:44.205 --> 00:04:46.826
Most people with albinism
are considered legally blind.

00:04:46.826 --> 00:04:49.222
So certainly wouldn't
be driving around Paris

00:04:49.222 --> 00:04:51.277
and like shooting at
anybody and expect to hit

00:04:51.277 --> 00:04:52.426
any of their targets.

00:04:52.426 --> 00:04:54.936
So this is terrible
information that's out there.

00:04:54.936 --> 00:04:58.098
I'm thinking this is getting
worse and worse and worse

00:04:58.098 --> 00:05:02.255
but I did see in one
of my research moments,

00:05:02.255 --> 00:05:04.647
I saw that there was a
support group called NOAH.

00:05:04.647 --> 00:05:07.436
NOAH's the National
Organization for Albinism

00:05:07.436 --> 00:05:08.928
and Hypopigmentation.

00:05:08.928 --> 00:05:11.533
It's a support group for people
living with this condition

00:05:11.533 --> 00:05:12.727
and their families.

00:05:12.727 --> 00:05:13.959
I got so excited.

00:05:13.959 --> 00:05:15.698
I called 'em instantly
and I was like, hey,

00:05:15.698 --> 00:05:16.761
I'm a fashion photographer.

00:05:16.761 --> 00:05:18.444
Let's show the world
the beauty of albinism.

00:05:18.444 --> 00:05:19.966
This is gonna be amazing!

00:05:19.966 --> 00:05:21.368
They said, get lost.

00:05:21.368 --> 00:05:22.565
(audience laughs)

00:05:22.565 --> 00:05:24.001
You know, I'm pretty persistent,
I'm kind of a New Yorker.

00:05:24.001 --> 00:05:25.414
I don't give up so easily.

00:05:25.414 --> 00:05:27.216
I kept going after them and asking them

00:05:27.216 --> 00:05:30.005
and trying to find out why
they told me to get lost

00:05:30.005 --> 00:05:32.363
and they eventually
made it very clear to me

00:05:32.363 --> 00:05:34.055
about their fear of exploitation,

00:05:34.055 --> 00:05:36.242
that every time there
was a magazine article

00:05:36.242 --> 00:05:37.480
about somebody with albinism,

00:05:37.480 --> 00:05:39.178
it was always the story about a victim.

00:05:39.178 --> 00:05:40.971
It was always sensational.

00:05:40.971 --> 00:05:43.030
It was always exploitative.

00:05:43.030 --> 00:05:45.056
It was always negative.

00:05:45.056 --> 00:05:46.684
I'm like, okay, I get it.

00:05:46.684 --> 00:05:47.696
I see this.

00:05:47.696 --> 00:05:48.712
I feel this.

00:05:48.712 --> 00:05:50.187
I understand this completely but that's,

00:05:50.187 --> 00:05:52.922
I can't find one positive
portrayal of albinism

00:05:52.922 --> 00:05:54.733
and it's just wild.

00:05:54.733 --> 00:05:56.942
So can, why don't we do
something strange here?

00:05:56.942 --> 00:05:59.829
Let's form a non-traditional partnership.

00:05:59.829 --> 00:06:02.910
Fashion photographer,
genetic support group,

00:06:02.910 --> 00:06:04.175
and together we'll collaborate

00:06:04.175 --> 00:06:06.816
and create a photographic
essay that celebrates

00:06:06.816 --> 00:06:10.134
the beauty of albinism and they agreed.

00:06:10.134 --> 00:06:11.433
I'm like, oh this is amazing!

00:06:11.433 --> 00:06:13.435
So Positive Exposure is born that day.

00:06:13.435 --> 00:06:15.755
In walks the first girl
I'm going to photograph.

00:06:15.755 --> 00:06:17.015
Her name is Christine.

00:06:17.015 --> 00:06:18.286
She's stunning.

00:06:18.286 --> 00:06:20.296
She's 5'9", long white
hair, she's amazing,

00:06:20.296 --> 00:06:23.417
but she walks into my studio
with her shoulders hunched,

00:06:23.417 --> 00:06:26.690
head down, no eye
contact, one word answers.

00:06:26.690 --> 00:06:30.757
This kid had zero self-esteem
as a direct result

00:06:30.757 --> 00:06:31.864
from the bullying,

00:06:31.864 --> 00:06:33.756
the teasing, the abuse,

00:06:33.756 --> 00:06:36.230
she experienced in the school environment

00:06:36.230 --> 00:06:39.199
because of her difference
and it was heartbreaking

00:06:39.199 --> 00:06:41.711
to see this beautiful kid
standing there like this.

00:06:41.711 --> 00:06:43.031
I didn't know what to do.

00:06:43.031 --> 00:06:44.506
How am I gonna photograph this kid?

00:06:44.506 --> 00:06:48.366
She's so vulnerable but just
the day before on the same set

00:06:48.366 --> 00:06:50.933
in my studio I did a Revlon
shoot with Cindy Crawford

00:06:50.933 --> 00:06:52.040
and I thought, you know,

00:06:52.040 --> 00:06:53.982
out of respect for this gorgeous kid,

00:06:53.982 --> 00:06:57.292
I'm gonna photograph her
like I would any supermodel.

00:06:57.292 --> 00:06:58.919
So the fan went on, the music went on,

00:06:58.919 --> 00:07:02.572
and I grabbed a mirror and I
held it up to her and I said,

00:07:02.572 --> 00:07:04.140
Christine, look at yourself.

00:07:04.140 --> 00:07:05.723
You're magnificent!

00:07:06.631 --> 00:07:09.841
And this kid looked in the
mirror and saw what I saw

00:07:09.841 --> 00:07:11.674
and she went from this

00:07:13.529 --> 00:07:14.895
to this.

00:07:14.895 --> 00:07:15.935
(audience laughs)

00:07:15.935 --> 00:07:17.983
And she exploded with
a smile that literally,

00:07:17.983 --> 00:07:20.097
literally lit up New York City.

00:07:20.097 --> 00:07:22.044
That's our beautiful Christine.

00:07:22.044 --> 00:07:23.043
(audience cheering)

00:07:23.043 --> 00:07:24.195
Thank you, thank you!

00:07:24.195 --> 00:07:25.192
(audience laughs)

00:07:25.192 --> 00:07:26.192
She loves applause.

00:07:26.192 --> 00:07:27.196
So Christine, now,

00:07:27.196 --> 00:07:29.598
she's gonna walk into school
the next day not like this,

00:07:29.598 --> 00:07:31.568
like she normally does but like this.

00:07:31.568 --> 00:07:35.313
She desperately needed to
change the way she saw herself.

00:07:35.313 --> 00:07:39.586
Her community desperately
needed to change the way

00:07:39.586 --> 00:07:41.429
that they saw her difference.

00:07:41.429 --> 00:07:44.314
So she created that moment,
that very first photo shoot,

00:07:44.314 --> 00:07:46.098
that Positive Exposure studio,

00:07:46.098 --> 00:07:48.969
the philosophy that drives
everything that we do

00:07:48.969 --> 00:07:51.994
and that philosophy is change how you see,

00:07:51.994 --> 00:07:53.766
see how you change.

00:07:53.766 --> 00:07:56.644
Those first images were in Life Magazine.

00:07:56.644 --> 00:07:59.281
It was in an article
called Redefining Beauty.

00:07:59.281 --> 00:08:00.920
Everybody saw it.

00:08:00.920 --> 00:08:02.385
I got lots of awards for it.

00:08:02.385 --> 00:08:03.567
It was great.

00:08:03.567 --> 00:08:04.672
It kind of put albinism on the map.

00:08:04.672 --> 00:08:05.997
The Albinism Foundation was thrilled.

00:08:05.997 --> 00:08:07.830
It went to all the different
foundations worldwide.

00:08:07.830 --> 00:08:09.758
As I was doing my fashion work,

00:08:09.758 --> 00:08:12.463
I'd show up in London and
we'd do a family photo shoot

00:08:12.463 --> 00:08:15.064
at a conference there or
in the UK or in Australia

00:08:15.064 --> 00:08:16.519
or in New Zealand,

00:08:16.519 --> 00:08:18.748
we started an organization
for a support group,

00:08:18.748 --> 00:08:19.767
all over the world.

00:08:19.767 --> 00:08:21.274
It raised a lot of noise.

00:08:21.274 --> 00:08:22.823
It was fantastic.

00:08:22.823 --> 00:08:25.133
When I came back to New York City

00:08:25.133 --> 00:08:26.205
while in the middle of all this,

00:08:26.205 --> 00:08:27.523
I received an award,

00:08:27.523 --> 00:08:30.012
one of the best awards that
I ever received in my life.

00:08:30.012 --> 00:08:32.167
It was an award from this organization

00:08:32.167 --> 00:08:33.666
called the Genetic Alliance.

00:08:33.666 --> 00:08:35.805
The Genetic Alliance is a coalition

00:08:35.805 --> 00:08:37.400
of all the genetic
support groups worldwide

00:08:37.400 --> 00:08:40.348
and as they were presenting the award,

00:08:40.348 --> 00:08:42.311
they explained that they see beauty

00:08:42.311 --> 00:08:44.836
in all these gorgeous
photographs of kids with albinism

00:08:44.836 --> 00:08:48.117
but there absolutely is a
universal message here -

00:08:48.117 --> 00:08:49.769
it's not about albinism,

00:08:49.769 --> 00:08:52.323
it's about all differences
and they asked me,

00:08:52.323 --> 00:08:53.633
would I be interested in going

00:08:53.633 --> 00:08:55.108
to one of the other genetic support groups

00:08:55.108 --> 00:08:57.015
that they represent and take photographs

00:08:57.015 --> 00:08:58.612
celebrating the beauty
of those gorgeous kids,

00:08:58.612 --> 00:09:01.284
celebrating the beauty
of their differences

00:09:01.284 --> 00:09:02.791
for their families?

00:09:02.791 --> 00:09:04.827
I was like, what an amazing idea.

00:09:04.827 --> 00:09:06.812
Of course, I would love to do that!

00:09:06.812 --> 00:09:08.647
But, you know, I wanted
to do my due diligence.

00:09:08.647 --> 00:09:10.732
I went back to those
scary medical textbooks

00:09:10.732 --> 00:09:13.718
to find out what the heck
a chromosome 18 anomaly was

00:09:13.718 --> 00:09:15.532
'cause that was the very next conference

00:09:15.532 --> 00:09:16.704
that they were representing.

00:09:16.704 --> 00:09:19.014
It was for the chromosome 18
registry and research society.

00:09:19.014 --> 00:09:21.259
So I figured, okay,

00:09:21.259 --> 00:09:22.601
I'm gonna go and figure it out

00:09:22.601 --> 00:09:23.851
and as I opened those medical textbooks

00:09:23.851 --> 00:09:27.316
to chromosome 18 anomalies
and that's what I saw.

00:09:27.316 --> 00:09:28.906
It was terrifying.

00:09:28.906 --> 00:09:30.916
I saw images of kids with cleft palates.

00:09:30.916 --> 00:09:33.339
I saw images of stillborns .

00:09:33.339 --> 00:09:35.793
I saw images of doctors
turning kids' heads like this.

00:09:35.793 --> 00:09:39.267
I saw, there were just
images of kids with tracs

00:09:39.267 --> 00:09:43.461
and feeding tubes and I, it
was trisomy 13, trisomy 18,

00:09:43.461 --> 00:09:47.378
tetrasomy 18, 18P and Q
minus and I'm thinking,

00:09:48.812 --> 00:09:50.119
this is horrible!

00:09:50.119 --> 00:09:51.116
I don't wanna do this.

00:09:51.116 --> 00:09:52.626
Albinism was so easy compared to this.

00:09:52.626 --> 00:09:55.875
This is frightening but I
went, I had committed to this,

00:09:55.875 --> 00:09:58.666
and it was in San Antonio,
Texas and I committed.

00:09:58.666 --> 00:10:00.864
So I went to this conference
and I was terrified

00:10:00.864 --> 00:10:02.742
but I walked into this conference

00:10:02.742 --> 00:10:04.947
and went down to the auditorium
where there were kids,

00:10:04.947 --> 00:10:07.832
kids and young adults being
entertained by a clown on stage

00:10:07.832 --> 00:10:11.127
making balloon animals and I
walked into that auditorium

00:10:11.127 --> 00:10:14.495
with these horrible images
burned in my head, terrified,

00:10:14.495 --> 00:10:17.201
but I walked in and I
was instantly surrounded

00:10:17.201 --> 00:10:19.540
by kids screaming with laughter.

00:10:19.540 --> 00:10:21.615
They were kids, they were
people in that audience.

00:10:21.615 --> 00:10:23.869
They were kids with
cleft palates and tracs

00:10:23.869 --> 00:10:26.582
and feeding tubes and mobility
issues but they were people,

00:10:26.582 --> 00:10:27.801
they were kids,

